    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>In Colombia, Echo of Another War</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Prof Sidney J Gluck letter on June 22 article holds aid package for Colombia's war on drugs suggests class-based intent to support one side in Colombia's civil strife</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The Senate's approval of a $1 billion aid package to Colombia as part of a war on drugs (front page, June 22) leaves us with the uneasy feeling that there is also a class-based intent to support one side in the civil strife in Colombia and recalls covert and overt aid to Central American countries during the cold war.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The Senate's approval of a $1 billion aid package to Colombia as part of a war on drugs (front page, June 22) leaves us with the uneasy feeling that there is also a class-based intent to support one side in the civil strife in Colombia and recalls covert and overt aid to Central American countries during the cold war.</p>
        <p>We can only hope that our money does not foster political hostilities in Colombia. Senator Mike DeWine of Ohio is quoted on the ''essence'' of our need to ''restore stability'' and ''combat the violent insurgents.'' Can this not escalate into interference in the internal affairs of a sovereign nation?</p>
        <p>SIDNEY J. GLUCK  New York, June 22, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a professor of social sciences at the New School for Social Research.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
